    "body": "**grdpaste** has a requirement that the two input grids have the same internal zcale/offset.  If you try a mix you get\r\n\r\n`grdpaste [ERROR]: Scale/offset not compatible!`\r\n\r\nOK.  So here are two grids with a scaling of 0.5:\r\n\r\n```\r\ngmt grdmath -R0/2/0/2 -I1 -rp 10 = a.grd=ns+s0.5\r\ngmt grdmath -R0/2/2/4 -I1 -rp 10 = b.grd=ns+s0.5\r\n```\r\n\r\nPer **grdinfo**, both have just the value 10 in them:\r\n\r\n```\r\ngmt grdinfo [ab].grd | grep v_max\r\na.grd: v_min: 10 v_max: 10 name: z\r\nb.grd: v_min: 10 v_max: 10 name: z\r\n```\r\n\r\nbut of course in reality the netCDF file has the values 20 and a scale of 0.5:\r\n\r\n```\r\nncdump a.grd\r\n...\r\n\t\tz:long_name = \"z\" ;\r\n\t\tz:scale_factor = 0.5 ;\r\n\t\tz:_FillValue = -32768s ;\r\n\t\tz:actual_range = 10., 10. ;\r\n...\r\ndata:\r\n\r\n z =\r\n  20, 20,\r\n  20, 20 ;\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo far, so good.  Let's paste the two grids together along the common y-level:\r\n\r\n`gmt grdpaste a.grd b.grd -Gc.grd`\r\n\r\ngmt grdinfo c.grd says scale factor is 1 and offset is 0, which is correct (we did not append any +s +o to the output file).  However, the min/max now says\r\n`c.grd: v_min: 10 v_max: 20 name: z`\r\n\r\nand `gmt grd2xyz c.grd` gives\r\n\r\n```\r\n0.5\t3.5\t10\r\n1.5\t3.5\t10\r\n0.5\t2.5\t10\r\n1.5\t2.5\t10\r\n0.5\t1.5\t20\r\n1.5\t1.5\t20\r\n0.5\t0.5\t20\r\n1.5\t0.5\t20\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo apparently b.grd is correctly read in and the 20s become 10, while a.grd is not scaled by 0.5 upon reading and hence we get a mix of 20s and 10s in the final output file.\r\n",
